0–Zesnulá","1450–1520":"1450–1520","1393–1430":"1393–1430","1388–1440":"1388–1440","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1393":"1393","1503":"1503","1415":"1415","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1411":"1411","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1520":"1520","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","Abt 1440":"okolo 1440","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Cruden, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Prestwich, Lancashire, England":"Prestwich, Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1420–1503":"1420–1503","1422–1475":"1422–1475","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1440–Female":"1440–Afdød","1450–1520":"1450–1520","1393–1430":"1393–1430","1388–1440":"1388–1440","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1393":"1393","1503":"1503","1415":"1415","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1411":"1411","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1520":"1520","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","Abt 1440":"omkring 1440","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Skotland","Cruden, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Skotland","England":"England, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Skotland","Prestwich, Lancashire, England":"Prestwich, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1420–1503":"1420–1503","1422–1475":"1422–1475","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1440–Female":"1440–Overleden","1450–1520":"1450–1520","1393–1430":"1393–1430","1388–1440":"1388–1440","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1393":"1393","1503":"1503","1415":"1415","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1411":"1411","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1520":"1520","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","Abt 1440":"circa 1440","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Schotland","Cruden, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Schotland","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland","Prestwich, Lancashire, England":"Prestwich, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1420–1503":"1420–1503","1422–1475":"1422–1475","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1440–Female":"1440–Deceased","1450–1520":"1450–1520","1393–1430":"1393–1430","1388–1440":"1388–1440","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1393":"1393","1503":"1503","1415":"1415","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1411":"1411","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1520":"1520","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","Abt 1440":"about 1440","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Cruden, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","England":"England, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Prestwich, Lancashire, England":"Prestwich, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in a (usually remote) nook or corner of land, from Old English and Middle English <i>hale</i>, dative of <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, hollow’, or a habitational name from a place so named such as Hale in Cheshire, Hampshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Holme Hale (Norfolk), Hale Street (Kent), and Haile (Cumberland). In northern England the word often has a specialized meaning, denoting a piece of flat alluvial land by the side of a river, typically one deposited in a bend. See   Haugh  . In southeastern England it often referred to a patch of dry land in a fen. In some cases the surname may be a habitational name from any of several places in England named with this fossilized inflected form, which would originally have been preceded by a preposition, e.g. <i>in the hale</i> or <i>at the hale</i>. This surname is also established in south Wales.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Céile</b> (see   McHale  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Halle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Halling","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire): habitational name from Hawling in Gloucestershire or possibly from Halling in Kent. Halling was named in Old English as ‘family or followers of a man called <i>Heall</i>’; Hawling may have the same etymology or it may have meant ‘people from Hallow’ (a place in Worcestershire named in Old English with <i>halh</i> + <i>haga</i> ‘enclosure’), or ‘people at the nook of land’, Old English <i>halh</i> (see   Hale   1).","German and Dutch: variant of   Helling  .","Swedish: cognate of   Hallin  , formed with the suffix <i>-ing</i> ‘belonging to’."]},{"name":"Halker","meanings":["English and Scottish: perhaps from an agent noun based on Middle English <i>halk</i> ‘nook, corner, recess’ (Old English <i>healc</i>, <i>healuc</i>, a derivative of <i>healh</i>; see   Hale  ), denoting someone who lived in or by a nook. This surname is now rare in Britain.","English: variant of   Hawker  ."]},{"name":"Hallam","meanings":["English (North Midlands): habitational name from Halam (Nottinghamshire) or from Kirk or West Hallam (Derbyshire), all named with the Old English dative plural <i>halum</i> ‘(at the) nooks or corners of land’ (from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’; see   Hale   1). The name may also be derived from Hallam in Sheffield (Yorkshire), sometimes called <i>Hallamshire</i>, named from Old English <i>hallum</i> ‘(at the) rocks’, the dative plural of Old English <i>hall</i> ‘stone, rock’, Old Norse <i>hallr</i>.","English: possibly a variant of   Allam   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Hales","meanings":["English (widespread, especially in the southeast): from the genitive singular or nominative plural form of Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’ (see   Hale  ).","Irish: when not of English origin, this may be a variant of   Healy   or   McHale  ."]},{"name":"Haugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Connor, Eamon.","Irish (Clare): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEachach</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eochu</i>’, a personal name which is probably a pet form of <i>Eochaidh</i>, <i>Eachaidh</i> (see   Hoey  ).","Scottish and English: from northern Middle English and Older Scots <i>halh</i>, <i>haugh</i> ‘a piece of flat alluvial land by the side of a river, typically one deposited in a bend’, also ‘river-meadow land’; either topographic for someone who lived near such a feature or habitational for someone who came from one of several places in Scotland and northern England called Haugh."]},{"name":"Hallows","meanings":["English: variant of   Hale   1, a topographic name from Middle English <i>hale</i>, Old English <i>halh</i> ‘hollow, nook, sheltered spot’. The final <i>-s</i> may indicate an original plural, but in some cases it is likely to be excrescent, a post-medieval modification of the surname."]},{"name":"Heal","meanings":["English:","topographic or habitational name for someone who lived in or by a nook or hollow, or at a place called with this word (from Middle English <i>hele</i>, Old English <i>heale</i>, dative singular of <i>healh</i> ‘nook or hollow’). Hele in Somerset derives from this word, but the surname arises chiefly from one or more of the many minor localities named Heal(e) or Hele in Devon. In southwestern England and Kent this is an equivalent of   Hale  .","in the southeast Midlands of England, perhaps a variant of   Hell   1."]},{"name":"Bagnall","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): habitational name from Bagnall or Bagnall in Alrewas, both in Staffordshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Badeca</i>, <i>Baduca</i> (from a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>beadu</i> ‘battle’) + Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’ (see   Hale  ) or <i>holt</i> ‘wood’ (see   Holt  ). In the 16th century the name was taken to Ireland, where it became established in Leinster."]},{"name":"Haile","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Ethiopian/Eritrean Lemlem, Senait, Bereket, Seifu, Abrehet, Amanuel, Berhane, Dawit, Dehab, Fekade, Fekadu, Hagos.","English: northern or occasional form of   Hale  , or a habitational name from a place called with Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, hollow’, such as Haile (Cumberland) or the frequent Hale (for example in Cheshire, Hampshire, Kent, and Lincolnshire).","English and Scottish: variant of   Hail  ."]},{"name":"Hail","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English, Older Scots <i>heil</i>, <i>hail</i> ‘healthy’ or ‘health’ (Old Norse <i>heill</i> ‘healthy’). This surname may well have become confused with the much more frequent   Hale   or, especially in Gloucestershire, with   Hailes  . Alternatively, in some cases the name may derive from the Old English personal name <i>Hægel</i>, from <i>hægel</i> ‘hail(stones)’, which may have survived into Middle English.","South German: variant of   Heil  ."]}]},{"name":"Patricia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Patricia</i>, feminine form of <i>Patricius</i>;  see  Patrick ."],"variants":[{"name":"Patricio","meanings":["form of English and Irish <b>Patrick</b>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Patricia Hale was born in 1420, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard Hale, was 27 and her mother, Eleanor Harbottle, was 32. She married William Hurst Watson in 1444, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1503, in her hometown, at the age of 83."},"et":{"1420–1503":"1420–1503","1422–1475":"1422–1475","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1440–Female":"1440–Surnud","1450–1520":"1450–1520","1393–1430":"1393–1430","1388–1440":"1388–1440","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1393":"1393","1503":"1503","1415":"1415","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1411":"1411","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1520":"1520","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","Abt 1440":"umbes 1440","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Cruden, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Prestwich, Lancashire, England":"Prestwich, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1420–1503":"1420–1503","1422–1475":"1422–1475","1415–1500":"1415–15